# Respect the Interview

Interviews cost time.

Engineers pause real work to evaluate candidates.

When someone comes unprepared:

It is not just a mistake.

> It is disrespecting the interviewer’s time.

---

# Interview Is About Readiness

An interview is simply checking:

> **Are you ready for the job?**

The process starts long before the interview.

---

# Step 1 — Your Resume

The first evaluation happens through your **resume**.

Prepare it carefully.

Include:

- academic scores
- institutions you studied at
- projects
- skills you are developing

Academic history shows **a pattern of consistency**.

---

# Step 2 — Study Other Resumes

Before finalizing your resume:

Look at **at least 50 resumes**.

Observe:

- layouts
- skill sections
- project descriptions
- clarity of presentation

This exercise teaches you what employers expect.

---

# Step 3 — Read Your Resume 100 Times

Your resume represents **you**.

Read it again and again.

Every line should answer:

> Why should a company hire me?

Once you do this carefully:

You begin to understand what the job requires.

---

# Step 4 — Build the Skills

Now start building those skills.

Practice consistently through:

- coding
- projects
- LeetCode
- GitHub
- technical learning

---

# Step 5 — Build Your Public Profile

Your resume should be supported by visible work.

Maintain consistency on:

- LinkedIn
- GitHub
- LeetCode

These platforms demonstrate **real effort over time**.

---

# Step 6 — Assume Your Resume Is Selected

Now the interview becomes real.

Before the interview:

Research:

- the company
- the product
- the engineering culture
- the interviewer (if possible)

Prepare thoughtful questions.

---

# Step 7 — Present Yourself Professionally

Interviews are professional interactions.

Be:

- prepared
- confident
- well dressed
- respectful

First impressions matter.

---

# Step 8 — The First Question

Almost every interview begins with the same question:

> **"Tell me about yourself."**

This question will appear throughout your career.

As a fresher:

Spend **at least one full week preparing this answer**.

Because this answer defines:

- your story
- your direction
- your seriousness as an engineer

---

# The Build → Delete → Rebuild Method

One powerful way to learn programming:

1. Build a small application  
2. Use tutorials or GPT if needed  
3. Delete the entire project  
4. Rebuild it from memory  

If stuck, go back to resources.

Then repeat.

> Real learning begins when the tutorial disappears.

---

# Skills Needed for a Modern AI Engineer

A modern AI engineer is a **full-stack engineer plus machine learning awareness**.

Technologies and tools you must practice include:

VSCode, terminal, Git, GitHub, Linux, Docker, ChatGPT, Claude Code, prompt engineering, ReactJS, NodeJS, REST APIs, Python, FastAPI, databases, APIs, debugging, system thinking, LeetCode, algorithms, data structures, supervised machine learning, unsupervised learning, feature engineering, model evaluation, deep learning fundamentals, LangChain, LangGraph, RAG systems, AI agents, distributed systems, and strong documentation habits.

---

# Final Thought

Software interviews do not test whether you know syntax.

They test whether you can be trusted to build software.

If ChatGPT can do your work,

> you are replaceable.

But if you can:

- understand problems
- think clearly
- design systems
- explain solutions

Then technology will always need you.

> Aim not to become someone who **knows programming**.  
> Aim to become someone who **thinks like an engineer**.
